rship of the European Economic Community; demonstrates how US détente policies created strain in the 'special relationship'; reveals the temporary shutdown of US-UK intelligence and nuclear co-operation; provides new insights in US-UK defence co-operation, and re-evaluates the US-UK relationship throughout the IMF Crisis.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aPolitical science. 4aInternational Relations 2019. 4aPolitical Studies 2021. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / General.2bisacsh  aBritish foreign policy.  aCold War.  aHenry Kissinger.  aRichard Nixon.  aSpecial Relationship.  aUS foreign policy.  aUS-UK relations.1 aRobb, Thomas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2014 eBook-Packagez978311128357940uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/9781526129383zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526129383zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526129383/original  a978-3-11-128357-9 Manchester University Press 2014 eBook-Packageb2014  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA